text.text: A Guide to Finsbury Park

Way over yonder in North London, one finds oneself in Finsbury Park, where late-night bowling is a boozy, raucous affair and the Arsenal/Tottenham rivalry is the main political agenda. Yep, sure, but what does one find there? You wanna know wargwarn, we wanna know wargwarn. The next logical step? Have it large, duhhh.
Best for… a sarnie, what else?

tip.text:
Tasty sandwiches, ample booze and enthusiastic chatter. Those are the obvious passions of Max, and his Finsbury Park shack is built on those three pillars, co-existing in true harmony. With a simple list of three or four gargantuan sarnies, a couple snacks and some punchy cocktails, he’s given himself plenty of time to sit and enjoy his creations and the company of other people enjoying his creations.

His magnum opus is the ham, egg ‘n’ chips of homemade focaccia, braised ham hock, shoestring fries and house-fermented piccalilli. The pillowy-soft focaccia and the crispy shoestring fries compliment each other more than Gen Zs on Instagram, whilst the runny egg ties it all together and gives you something to mop up with escapee pieces of ham hock. It’s a messy affair, so don’t wear white and take someone who has already seen you at your worst.

text.text: Mad Max and his salacious sarnies are the stuff of local legend round these parts. No, the menu isn’t extensive but damn baby, these are some big-ass fuckin' sandwiches. Don’t step up in here thinking sandwiches are a sort of pseudo-lunch ‘cos Max and Chris will school you. The menu is tongue in cheek, the booze is cheap and the vibes are chilled.
Best for… stretching those pins

tip.text: A 5 mile walk along the ex-railway that used to run between Finsbury Park and Alexandra Palace. The park can be accessed at several points along the trail and is a tranquil escape from the city. As a nature reserve, it is also home to plenty of woodland creatures.

text.text: Follow in the footsteps of locomotives from days gone with this charming walkway on a former railway line. You’ll feel like a proper urban woodland creature, feeling your way through the forest and the forgotten statues, under the graffiti and vine-infested railway arches. There’s even a cheeky half-pipe if you’re ‘bout that skater life. Numerous entry points between Muswell Hill and Finsbury Park.
Best for... pizza mind

tip.text:
Yard Sale Pizza is straight outta Clapton (where it started as a Supper Club) and yet here they are with a second branch in FP, bringing that high-quality takeaway pizza to hungry North Londoners. The menu is short and sweet but you can expect sick flavours and dope ingredients. Oh, McAuley Culkin played at their initial launch party. Yeah, pretty bloody random.

We love the butternut squash, goats cheese, rocket and honey drizzle (no mozzarella). For the real meat lovers the pepperoni, fennel sausage, spicy beef, black olives, mixed peppers and mushrooms never goes amiss. It's not all dough though with a selection of salads and beers.

tip.text:
We’re big into places where the passion and knowledge of the owners radiates outwards, and Mountgrove Bothy is one such spot. It’s a cosy and intimate neighbourhood wine bar hidden away on an indistinct street in Highbury, where a relaxed vibe is paired with an unrivalled selection of rare wines. And we really mean that - if you love wine you need to come here and chat to Gareth, who'll take you on a tour from peppy orange tipples from Canterbury to full bodied Merlots from Croatia.

You’ll find fairly affluent looking locals either on the romantic tip, tasting wines or catching up over small plates that are really worth sampling. The kitchen is a basic operation but that seems to just bring the best out of the chefs who create simple, delicious dishes: previous menu picks have featured a beautifully nutty spelt tagliatelle, lamb neck flatbread and dexter beef tartare. A swishy haunt to impress a mate, romance a date, or just enjoy a delicious glass on your ones.

Best for... a raucous spot of bowling

tip.text: Rowans is the type of place where dreams can be made, and marbles just as easily lost. It's a Dojo favourite for the pure raucous funhouse vibes: ten pin bowling, a retro games room, cocktail slush-puppies and two wild karaoke rooms, able to squeeze in 24 bods at a push. Be warned, you'll need to forget any notions about self-image before heading here. We've seen all kinds of cool cats broken.

Best for… late night bagel bitez

tip.text:
None of that fake herby smell wafting out of Subway... the scent of fresh bagels and challah bread wafting out of the Happening Bagel Bakery is the genuine article, and is the stuff dreams are made of. It stays open until 2am too, which makes it perfect drunken munchies territory.

Every conceivable type of bagel is up for grabs here, and you can order them packed with fillings like smoked salmon, minted lamb, or salt beef and dill turkey. There's also fresh croissants, savoury pastries, and doughnuts.

text.text: Some people hit McDonalds after a night-out, others go for a cheeky bagel. It is what it is, but the latter is definitely far more up our street - can’t beat the wafting aromas of freshly baked bagels now can you? All manner of bagels, all manner of fillings, so there’s pretty much nothing you can complain about, just thank the cosmos that these guys are open til 2AM, so you can line your stomach on your way home: hangover cure stage 1.
Best for... hot Asian comfort food

tip.text:
Dotori is your quintessential neighbourhood haunt - the kind of place that anyone living within a two-mile radius feels quietly smug about and estate agents use as a selling point on Zoopla.

It’s a small, chaotic Korean-Japanese hybrid spot with a perpetual queue outside of people waiting for a hit of something hot and comforting. The Japanese offerings are perfectly fine but the reason to come is the Korean stuff. Succulent shredded beef with a fiery broth and rice; bokum bap sprinkled with sizzled pork belly, spring onion and scrambled egg; or a bouncy-but-crisp seafood pancake, dunked in soy. It's a wild ride of bold flavours and interesting textures that just makes you feel good - and with most things under a tenner, it's cheaper than a therapist.

In terms of service, it’s a matter of where you sit, literally. Don't be afraid to get up and ask for something and just remember how grateful you were for the staff’s efficiency when you were queuing outside in the cold.

tip.text:
The Faltering Fullback’s charm begins with its vine-clad exterior and ends with its gorgeous terraced beer garden. Seriously, it’s one of, if not the, best beer gardens in London. You know what? Scratch the beer, this is one of the best gardens, period. Ya hear dat, Kew? Ya hear dat, Kensington? Yeah, you heard.

The inside is pretty OK as well: pool tables, big-screen sportz for big-sportz fans, banging Thai food, quirky decor and all the beers you could reasonably expect. Honestly though, get yourself in that garden, pal. Just be prepared to fight for your spot, especially if there’s been any hint of sun that day - you know how we get.

text.text: Quite possibly one of the best pubs in London (particularly if you’re a sports fan), The Faltering Fullback’s charm begins with its vine-clad exterior and ends with its gorgeous, terraced beer garden. The inside? Pool to shoot, Thai food to scoff, beers to drown your sorrows in and big-time screens for big-time sports happenings. Honestly though, get yourself in that garden pal.
Best for… dem grilled goodz

tip.text:
For a Turkish restaurant in one of the main Turkish neighbourhoods in London to be constantly rammed is a good indication of it being pretty special. Gokyuzu is known for delivering top quality dishes, but also for serving MASSIVE portions at seriously decent prices. Can't argue with that.

The large mixed meze is ideal for a hungry group, and they also do a range of Turkish pizzas which make a nice change from the Italian norm.

text.text: Listen closely. Listen. That’s the sound of people speaking Turkish a.k.a the ultimate seal of approval. None of that Tripadvisor certificate of excellence malarkey - the people have spoken motherfuckers. There’s nothing glamorous about this spot but tucking into the mixed grill up in here is a weighty and emotional experience all at once. Yeah, you might need to be rolled out of the restaurant, but that can't be a bad sign.
Best for… f*ck, that's deli-cious

tip.text: A cafe/deli that seems to have the balance just about right. The healthy and ethically sourced products lining the walls are certainly worth a gander including meats and cheeses from France and proper wine. It's not the most comfy cafe about but the coffee is top notch, so maybe a takeaway is in order. And look out for their evening events which includes stuff like gin and wine tasting.

text.text: Locating a stellar deli is fundamental when traversing any ends, so this is warg1 in Finsbury Park: ethically sourced produce, meats and cheeses from our pals over in France, great coffee, wine & gin tasting events. Sound good? Yep, thought as much - whether you’re looking to pick up some ingredients to whip up a storm back at your yard or you fancy something on the go, Deli at 80 have got you covered.
Best for... board games, beers and bantz

tip.text:
We never watched Cheers, due to not being American and being around 3 years old at the time of its last ever show. But we know there was that one bar that they all loved so damn much they named their show after it - that's how we imagine locals feel about Bedford Tavern. This grand, atmospheric public house was boarded up until fairly recently; now it pushes out a fantastic selection of craft beers, very highly rated burgers; and one of the friendliest atmospheres in North London.

It's a cosy tavern really made for grabbing a group of friends together and losing all sense of time, aided and abetted by some beer or wine. On other nights, you'll find pub quizzes, live music and, of course, late hours on the weekends when it fills with beautiful late-night laughter.

Best for... a real cheap eat

tip.text: It'd be pretty easy to pass this place by, but let's just get one thing straight: large mains here are between £4-6. Whilst the menu seems to cater to the lunchtime crowd with its sandwiches and jacket potatoes, we suggest going for the Moroccan offerings: the tagines are really delicious with spinach, potato, aubergine and lemon coming to the fore. Nothing too fancy in terms of decor or ambience but you get a lot of bang for your buck here, a rarity in London. Finish off with a pastry and you'll feel real content.

Best for... a daytime cotch

tip.text:
We're big into theatre cafes because, aside from when things begin to swing at showtime, they're tranquil, comfy places, ripe for an afternoon cotch. Park Theatre is in that mould: a softly lit, lazy place where cultured locals come to chew the fat, pinch some free wifi and just generally let the day roll on by, aided by the gentle hubbub of life itself.

The menu actually covers a fair amount including breakfast options, sandwiches and stone-baked pizzas coming in at around a tenner. Union coffee and the usual cocktail suspects complete the fuelling.
